Jenkins is an open-source automation server used to automate tasks related to building, testing, and deploying software. It supports continuous integration (CI) and continuous delivery (CD), making it a popular choice for developers.

Introduction to Jenkins
Jenkins Overview:

Jenkins is a self-contained automation server.
It can be installed through native system packages, Docker, or run standalone with a Java Runtime Environment (JRE).
Jenkins is highly extensible through plugins.
Key Features:

Pipeline: Jenkins' main feature for defining automated processes.
Plugins: Extend Jenkins functionality.
Blue Ocean: A modern interface for Jenkins.
Implementation Steps
Installation:

Install Jenkins via native packages, Docker, or standalone JRE.
Configuration:

Set up Jenkins using the post-installation setup wizard.
Install suggested plugins for enhanced functionality.
Creating Pipelines:

Use Jenkins Pipeline to define your CI/CD processes.
Create Jenkinsfiles to specify pipeline stages.
Using Plugins:

Install and configure plugins to extend Jenkins capabilities.
Examples include GitHub integration, Docker support, and more.
